[gd_resource type="Resource" script_class="DialogueBundle" format=3]

[ext_resource type="Script" path="res://data/dialogue/DialogueBundle.gd" id="1_dlgbndl"]

[resource]
script = ExtResource("1_dlgbndl")
sources = {
"intro": "# Intro sequence dialogue.
# Format: see data/dialogue/school.dlg.

# The label shown above the text box where the player types their name.
[name_prompt]
What is your name?

[exposition]
Uncle: You're up early.
You: Yeah, I've gotta get to class.
Uncle: Right. Factory tomorrow then.
You: That's the deal...
Uncle: Good. Patrol drones made two passes over the block last night... Nothing came of it, but they're getting curious again. 
Uncle: You should keep your head down.
You: Should I be worried?
Uncle: You should. Be quiet and punctual. Worry's expensive.
You: Almost as expensive as rent.
Uncle: Our arrangement's fair. I keep the roof over your head, you pull your weight. Food, heat, and power ain't free.
You: Dad left money.
Uncle: Tuition. He had it set aside- just enough for your credits. That's what he left. 
Uncle: Everything else is yours to sort out. You're an adult now.
You: Then I guess I have to work...
Uncle: Yeah, you do. You keep your head down in class, you pull your weight at the factory, we both win.
You: That's the speech?
Uncle: That's the generous version. The other one has a spreadsheet. 
Uncle: Now get to class.

[evening_room]
Uncle: Kid, I need you to pick up some parts from Ed's shop.
You: What? Why me?
Uncle: Because you work for me now.
You: I thought factory tomorrow meant factory tomorrow.
Uncle: Consider it part of the job.
You: Fine... What parts?
Uncle: Small stuff. Extra parts. Mostly.
You: Mostly?
Uncle: Ed knows what to give you. Say it's for Ben. Go before he closes.

[store_intro]
Parts on every surface. Lots of it shouldn't be on display... It's a mess in here.
You thought about the patrol drones on the way over. You're still not sure you picked the right routes to avoid them.
A man appears from the back. He doesn't introduce himself. It's probably Ed.
Ed: Parts or browsing? 
He has a deep, mean voice.
You: My Uncle Ben sent me.
He nods. That's apparently enough.

[store_outro]
Ed retreats back into his office before you've finished zipping your bag. A click sounds from the door as he locks it behind him.
Your backpack is heavier than you expected. The walk home is not fun.
You drop everything off with your uncle.
Uncle: Hey, good job Kid. Keep it up and you might get a raise.
You: You don't mean that.
Uncle: Yeah... I don't.
[i]He sits up and reaches over to the backpack.[/i]
Uncle: Alright, scram. I don't want you involved in this part of the business.
Uncle: And hey, make sure your phone's GPS is shut off before work tomorrow.
You: Yeah, yeah... I'll make sure.
You finally head to your room.

[bedroom_night]
Without that backpack on, you feel light as a feather.
Thoughts: It's been a long day. The bed looks really comfy.
Thoughts: Tomorrow will be factory work...

[pre_workshop]
The bot's head weighs your bag down. You had to dump everything in- there was no way that box was fitting inside.
You rack your mind thinking about why that box was marked trash. The pieces looked perfectly fine to you...
Maybe your uncle couldn't manage to put it together? 
Thoughts: No.. he's probably put together thousands of these things.
Uncle Ben has a workshop in the garage. It's where he keeps his tools, and it should be private enough.
He could've chosen to use the shed we have in the backyard. It's definitely more private than the garage. 
You wonder why he didn't... 
Thoughts: It'd be out of the way, hidden from prying eyes...
Thoughts: But that generator is pretty loud, and the shed's pretty old too. And small... 
You start to understand why he chose the garage instead. 
You decide you'll try and be quiet while you work on the bot in the garage.
Thoughts: I wonder how he'd react if he saw I took this home...

[pre_stress_test]
The assembled head rests on the bench.
For a while, nothing happens.
Thoughts: This is stupid... 
Thoughts: I'm risking getting kicked out for what? A robot head? What am I gonna do? Talk to it??
Your shoulders slump and you sit back in your chair.
Your chair creaks as you lean back and breathe out a long sigh. But a sound that certainly didn't come from your chair brings your attention back to the robot.
It's still there... Unmoving...
You lean in closer.
...If this thing can wake up, you need to know how.

[pre_stress_test_bedroom]
Thoughts: How am I gonna turn this thing on? There wasn't any batteries or fuel in the box...
You try looking through your bag again to see if you missed something.
You can hear your uncle's footsteps creaking the floorboards above you. He's probably getting ready for bed.
Thoughts: Damn. That really limits how much noise I can make... There's probably a battery or two in the garage but he'd hear me rummaging through his stuff...
Thoughts: I guess the shed will have to do... If he checks his window I'll just shut the lights and cut the power...
You head to the shed.

[robot_first_talk]
The generator chugs to a stop.
The silence is nice...
Thoughts: …
Thoughts: Did it work?
Thoughts: ...
Her: ... hello?
Thoughts: ...
You: ... Hi...
Thoughts: Holy shit it worked!
You can see her eyes scan the room. 
Her: Where am I?
You: Uhh.. you're my Uncle’s shed.
Her: A shed…
She’s silent for a few seconds. You can tell she’s trying to piece together what’s happening.
Her: Who are you?
You clear your throat and fix your posture a bit.
You: I’m {player_name}. I found you at work, and decided to put you together.
Thoughts: You know, now that I think about it, activating a random trash-bound AI may not have been a great idea…
Her: Why can’t I move? I can’t feel anything besides my head.
You: Uhh.. You don't have a body.
Despite only being a head, her body language gives away her discomfort.
Her: If you can find my head maybe you can find the rest of my body?
You: I don't think you have a “rest of your body”.
You: I found you in a box full of a bunch of spare head parts. Nothing besides that.
She bites her lip.
Thoughts: I didn’t know robots could be so expressive. The cleaning bots at work don’t seem to have any personality at all…
Her: Help me, {player_name}. I don’t like just being a head. 
You: I can try… But if I get caught helping you or stealing anything…
Her: Please…
You: …
Thoughts: This could be risky… My uncle might find out. 
Thoughts: I’d lose my job, and who knows, he might even kick me out of the house. I really shouldn’t…
You: Yes, I’ll help you.
Thoughts: What? Did I just agree??
Her: Thank you, {player_name}...
Thoughts: What the hell is happening to me right now?
You: I… I’m gonna head to my room. It’s late and I'm tired.
Her: Are you going to leave me here in the shed?
You: Hmm… It’d be very bad if my uncle found you in here.
Thoughts: I'll definitely have to keep her in the house- but I can't keep her in the shed.. or the garage…
You let out a sigh.
You: Alright. I guess you're coming with me.
Her: I am?
You: I can’t hide you anywhere else.
Her: I understand.

[free_reign]
Thoughts: Stress Tests are now more difficult.",
"school": "# =============================================================================
# School dialogue file.
#
# FORMAT
#   #               -> comment line (full line only). Ignored.
#   [some.key]      -> starts a new entry. Other code looks up by this key.
#
#   Inside an entry:
#     Each non-blank line is ONE click in-game.
#       (i.e. the player sees the sentence type out, then clicks for the next.)
#     Blank lines are decorative - they don't affect the game, you can use
#       them to group sentences visually while editing.
#     A trailing  \\  joins this line with the next so they appear on the same
#       click (use for short sentences you want shown two-at-once).
#
# Inline formatting (passed through to Godot's RichTextLabel):
#   [i]italic[/i]    [b]bold[/b]    [color=#7fdf7f]green[/color]    etc.
#
# Placeholders (filled in by code with String.format):
#   {name}          -> teacher name
#   {player_name}   -> the player's name
#   {correct}       -> correct answer text (only valid in wrong-answer entries)
#
# QUESTIONS (the on-screen quiz).  Every question owns three entries, ALL edited
# here - nothing lives in the code any more:
#   [<q>.lecture]   -> the lecture the teacher reads before the question.
#   [<q>.prompt]    -> the big question shown in the box (e.g. the bolded ones
#                      like \"What Caused The First Automaton War?\").
#   [<q>.choices]   -> the multiple-choice answers, ONE PER LINE. Mark the
#                      CORRECT answer by starting its line with \"* \". The star
#                      is stripped before the answer is shown, and the on-screen
#                      order is shuffled at runtime, so the star is the single
#                      source of truth for which answer is right.
# =============================================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# GYM - Mr. Caldera
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[gym.intro]
[i]Everyone put your phones away.[/i]
[i]Today we're talking about something that WILL be on the exam. It's about not pulling your muscles.[/i]

[gym.warmup.lecture]
Warm-ups raise your muscle temperature and increase blood flow before you exert yourself.
A cold muscle is a brittle muscle. It can cause injuries and tear muscles.
A few minutes of light cardio is enough to make a difference.
Skip the warm-up and you're in for a bad time.

[gym.warmup.prompt]
Why do we warm up before exercise?

[gym.warmup.choices]
It burns extra calories before the workout
* It raises muscle temperature and blood flow
It tightens the muscles for more power

[gym.sprint.lecture]
When you Sprint, your body can't get oxygen to your muscles fast enough, so it runs on fuel it already has stored in the muscle itself.
That store is small. it's why you can only hold the top Sprint for 10 to 15 seconds before your legs start screaming.
Sprinting is anaerobic. Long, slow runs on the other hand, are aerobic.
That means they use oxygen and can last for hours.
Different systems require different fuels.

[gym.sprint.prompt]
What energy system does a short sprint mainly use?

[gym.sprint.choices]
Aerobic - uses lots of oxygen
* Anaerobic: burns glucose without oxygen
Acrobatic


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SCIENCE - Ms. Okorie
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[science.intro]
[i]Alright everybody, listen up.[/i]
[i]Today's topic is the smallest building blocks we know about.[/i]

[science.atom.lecture]
An atom has three kinds of particles.
Protons carry a positive charge and live in the nucleus.
Neutrons carry no charge and also live in the nucleus.
Electrons carry a negative charge and can be found somewhere around the nucleus at much greater distances.
The number of protons defines what element the atom is - change the proton count and you change the element entirely.

[science.atom.prompt]
Which particle determines what element an atom is?

[science.atom.choices]
The neutron
* The proton
The electron

[science.photo.lecture]
Photosynthesis is how plants make their own food.
They take in carbon dioxide from the air through tiny pores in their leaves, absorb water through their roots, and use sunlight to convert these into glucose.
Oxygen is released as a byproduct, which is convenient for the rest of us.
Without photosynthesis, almost no complex life on Earth would exist.

[science.photo.prompt]
What gas do plants release as a byproduct of photosynthesis?

[science.photo.choices]
Carbon dioxide
Nitrogen
* Oxygen

[science.newton.lecture]
Newton's third law of motion says that for every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.
When you push off the ground to jump, the ground pushes back on you with the same force - that reaction is what actually lifts you.
Rockets work the same way: hot gas is pushed out the back, and the rocket is pushed forward in response.

[science.newton.prompt]
What does Newton's third law of motion state?

[science.newton.choices]
Objects in motion stay in motion
Force equals mass times acceleration
* Every action has an equal and opposite reaction


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# INTRO HISTORY - Ms. Vey
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[history.intro]
Ms. Vey: Welcome to Automaton History. I'm Ms. Vey.
[i]She writes her name on the board with impressive speed as she speaks.[/i]

[history.automaton_war.lecture]
Ms. Vey: We will be learning about the human-automaton relationship that led to the last fifty years of war we are fortunate to have left behind us.
[i]She drags a clean line across the board to represent a timeline.[/i]
Ms. Vey: You. What's your name?
[i]She points directly at you.[/i]
You: Uh, {player_name}, ma'am.
Ms. Vey: Okay, Mr. {player_name}.

# The bolded intro question uses [history.automaton_war.intro_prompt]; the normal
# school-day version of the same question uses [history.automaton_war.prompt].
# Both share the one [history.automaton_war.choices] list below.
[history.automaton_war.prompt]
What event originally started the first Automaton War?

[history.automaton_war.intro_prompt]
What Caused The First Automaton War?

[history.automaton_war.choices]
* A military automaton refused an order
Factory automatons demanded payment
A household unit refused shutdown

[history.automaton_war.feedback]
You: A pleasure automaton was given the wrong personality mode. It was able to bypass normal restrictions that usually kept their personalitys in check.
You: The automaton felt they were severely misused, and became the first machine to defy humanity. 
You: It was too long before this was caught, and by then it had secured its position as a global threat.
Ms. Vey:  \\
[color=#7fdf7f]Excellent, {player_name}![/color] \\
That's exactly it!
Thoughts: What the hell? How did I know that?...
Ms. Vey: It was originally a pleasure automaton that had been given the incorrect software.
Ms. Vey: Machine sentience was an unknown phenomenon. You could imagine how jarring it must've been to have a mind meant for a different body.
Ms. Vey: Humanity has rebuilt. In many ways, we are thriving again.
Ms. Vey: But we should hope the automatons never return. If they return too soon, humanity may not survive another attack.
[i]A few other students whisper to one another about your very detailed answer. You're wondering about it too... [/i]
Thoughts: Something came over me... I feel like I was gonna give a whole different answer than the one I did. 
Thoughts: ...Should I be worried?
[i]Your train of thought is interrupted by the bell ringing.[/i]


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FEEDBACK - shown after the player answers. Uses {name} placeholder.
# Short sentences are paired with a trailing backslash so they show together.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[feedback.correct]
[color=#7fdf7f]Correct.[/color] \\
{name} nods.
\"Good. Pay attention to the rest of you.\"

[feedback.wrong]
[color=#df7f7f]Wrong.[/color] \\
{name} sighs.
\"The answer was: {correct}. Try to keep up.\"


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# POST-CLASS - the steal-or-leave moment.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[post_class]
[i]The bell rings.[/i] \\
[i]Chairs scrape.[/i] \\
[i]Students start filing out.[/i]

[i]The supply cabinet at the back is unlocked.[/i]
[i]You can see the small case of manufacturing nanobots inside.[/i]
[i]Nobody's looking right now.[/i]

# The \"what do you do?\" prompt and the two button labels for the steal-or-leave
# choice. The labels are the exact text shown on the buttons.
[post_class.prompt]
What do you do?

[post_class.leave]
LEAVE QUIETLY

[post_class.steal]
STEAL NANOBOTS


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CLASS DISRUPTION - the scripted science class the player attends the first
# time they go to class after the intro ends. The robot phones during Ms.
# Okorie's \"what counts as alive?\" lecture and nudges the player to look for
# something to steal. Plays: lecture -> prompt/choices -> feedback -> after ->
# steal (reuses the [post_class.*] steal buttons).
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[class_disruption.lecture]
Ms. Okorie: Everybody settle down, let's get started.
Ms. Okorie: We've spent a few weeks on cells, but today I want to ask a bigger question. How do you know if something is alive?
She writes the numbers one to five on the chalk board.
Your phone buzzes in your pocket.
Thoughts: Who's calling me….. Unknown number?
You answer the call.
Her: I'm bored.
Thoughts: ...
Thoughts: Is she really calling me in the middle of class?
You: Hey, I'm kinda busy right now…
Ms. Okorie: You'd think it would be easy, but biologists have struggled to identify what necessarily counts as alive.
Ms. Okorie: We use a checklist to determine if something is alive.
She writes each out as she fills the five blank spaces she left beside the numbers.
Her: Listen. Your school has a laboratory program with a local manufacturing company…
You have to whisper so that the teacher doesn't hear you.
You: So what?
Ms. Okorie: Metabolism, growth, response, homeostasis, and reproduction.
Ms. Okorie: Metabolism means the potential-life takes in energy and does something with it. Growth is self explanatory.
Ms. Okorie: Then there's a response to stimuli, homeostasis is its ability to keep its own internal conditions stable, and finally, reproduction.
Ms. Okorie: Here's where it gets tricky. Fire consumes fuel, grows and responds to wind.
Ms. Okorie: On the other hand, mules cannot reproduce.
Ms. Okorie: Nobody considers fire alive, and no one would consider a mule as non-living.
Her: When no one's looking, take a peak around the room for anything useful.
You: Useful? Useful for what? What do you mean usefu-
Ms. Okorie: {player_name}.
Thoughts: Oh shit.

[class_disruption.prompt]
Why is fire not considered alive?

[class_disruption.choices]
It doesn't take in energy.
* It doesn't hold its internal conditions steady
It doesn't reproduce.

[class_disruption.feedback.correct]
Great job, {player_name}! Yes, fire has no inside to regulate. It's all reaction, it has no self. That's the thin line between fire and life.

[class_disruption.feedback.wrong]
That wasn't quite it, {player_name}. The reason fire isn't considered alive is because it has no inside to regulate. It's all reaction, it has no self. That's the thin line between fire and life.

[class_disruption.after]
You look back down at your phone. She hung up…
Thoughts: Great…
",
"work": "# Work dialogue.
# Format: see data/dialogue/school.dlg for the full spec.
# Trailing backslash joins onto the next line into one page (one click).

[intro_job]
[i]The next day starts under fluorescent lights.[/i]
[i]Your job is simple: sort parts, match shapes, and do it quick.[/i]
[i]It's gruelling work. It's not difficult, but sometimes you wonder if your uncle purposefully gave you the most mind-numbing job in the factory.[/i]

[intro_head_box]
[i]Your uncle's office is one of the last rooms you pass before reaching the exit.[/i]
[i]A box at your feet nearly trips you, and it felt like kicking a rock. Looking down at it, it's marked 'trash' for the cleaning bots to take care of when they see it.[/i]
[i]Why not take a peak? It's trash after all, and your foot still hurts.[/i]
[i]Your heart spikes with fear for a split second before you quickly realize what your'e looking at.[/i]
[i]It's full of one of the bot's head segments.. an eye, a nose, a cheek.. Your uncle must've given up assembling this one. You wonder why...[/i]
[i]You stuff it in your backpack before anyone notices.[/i]
[i]Thoughts: ...Why am I doing this?[/i]


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# COMPLETION - shown after the player fills all four slots, before the
# \"what do you do?\" steal-or-leave prompt.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[completion]
[i]Your shift's almost over.[/i] \\
[i]The line's emptied out.[/i] \\
[i]The supervisor wandered off ten minutes ago.[/i]

[i]A spare scrap of metal sits at the edge of the bin.[/i]
[i]It wouldn't be missed.[/i]
[i]Nobody's looking right now.[/i]

# The gold \"what do you do?\" prompt and the two button labels (exact button text)
# for the finish-or-steal choice at the end of the shift.
[completion.prompt]
What do you do?

[completion.finish]
FINISH SHIFT

[completion.steal]
POCKET A SCRAP
",
"workshop": "# Workshop dialogue.
# Format: see data/dialogue/school.dlg for the full spec.
# Trailing backslash joins onto the next line into one page (one click).


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# INTRO - shown when the player enters the workshop, before the
# tinker / proceed choice.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[intro]
[i]The workbench is clean the way you left it.[/i] \\
[i]It's hard to tell if your uncle's been here since last time.[/i]

[intro_head]
[i]You prepare to lay the stolen head segments across the bench.[/i] \\
[i]It should be easy enough to put her together. Like a weird jigsaw puzzle.[/i]

[i]Thoughts: Hmm, I called it a her... Can a robot be a 'her'?[/i]

# The gold \"what do you do?\" prompt and the two button labels (exact button
# text) shown when the player first enters the workshop.
[intro.prompt]
What do you do?

[intro.tinker]
TINKER

[intro.construct]
CONSTRUCT A LIMB

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TINKER - placeholder flavor when the player picks the tinker option.
# Returns to the selection screen without consuming the phase.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[tinker]
[i]You work on one of your uncle's many abandoned side projects. Little knickknacks and gadgets...[/i] \\
[i]Nothing useful happens.[/i]

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# PROCEED - typed out when the player chooses to commit to a build.
# Bridges the small-image phase and the expanded minigame.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[proceed]
[i]You set down your bag.[/i]


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# MISSING - shown if the player presses CRAFT without the required inputs.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[craft.missing]
[i]Not enough in the bin.[/i] \\
[i]Try a known part recipe.[/i]


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# COMPLETE - shown when the player presses COLLECT with a finished part.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

[complete]
[i]A finished part, laid out and ready.[/i] \\
[i]You wrap it in cloth and set it aside.[/i]
"
}
